<p>
  Kenya is consistently one of the highest-rated origins in the specialty coffee world. Its coffee is defined by <strong>vivid, wine-like acidity, complex layered flavors, and exceptional clarity</strong> — a combination that commands some of the highest prices at auction and captivates sommeliers, baristas, and coffee drinkers worldwide.
</p>

<p>
  What distinguishes Kenya's coffee industry as much as its terroir is its <strong>grading and auction system</strong>. The Nairobi Coffee Exchange (NCE) runs weekly auctions where every lot is cupped and graded before sale. Transparency is structural — buyers bid on quality they've verified, producers are rewarded for quality, and the system creates strong incentives to maintain standards. This institutional rigor is a major reason Kenyan coffee quality is so consistently high.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Kenya at a Glance</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Key varieties:</strong> SL28, SL34, Ruiru 11, Batian<br />
    <strong>Processing:</strong> Washed (double-washed)<br />
